In Antwarp 15 march 81
London wus scawen
S. my last to you was on the 8 curitt to which referre you, sence recd
yd of 25 puss in the first, intend this week to send forward by aray
of rporte & dover one packett of lace, which I doubt nott butt whis
arrived shall prove well to content, not onely in assortement butt
in prijses also, which shall desire you to sell for my acctt. as best you
can pto see how that trade will render, for in case wee can finde a good
acctt: by itto shall imploy a £1000: that way & be willing to comply
with you there n iyd on any reasonable termes, for & do promise
mij self to have that com as well if not better then any other
what soever on this side I do not approve to send as yett any laces
in tjkes, till you shall have seen what I dm ablet to send, intrim
all the tykes I brought in last winter are packt & sent to Bruges
out of which shall send you one bale, of a curious & neat assortem
almost exact toyd order, according to the inclosed invoyce, which
in case you peruse, you will finde cheaper them ever any arecome
to England, for I pickt them up when the worckmen wanted mony
some 3 & some ½ & some a month sence for the cost pleaseto qve
yd curitt creditt & acc ording you finde them please to advise for
I have secured yett neare too peeces, thought I can not have them yett
in 2 months. as for our callicoes please to buy in case you finde

S. my last to uouwas on the 4: curitt, sence recd. yd of 21 teast atte st
I doubt he will hold itt out as long he can, yett he can notwade itt as
I thinck I have recd. the small blle sent by klercks the goods prove tollem
ble, excapt N. 192 which hath a thread like a cours dosen, yett the
cullour will lett itt off, I have lookt over the pattarnes of the 10 cloth
which you intend to send mee theiy promise very well, so could wish
them here, for towards easter I hope to have some sale, & as soone as these
are gon shall send pu for few more, for me thinckes itt will be & is
the best way, to avoijde restants to have buttefew att atime & the oftend
please to advise when you have shipt the speanish cloathes: yd bill
of £130: is accepted I hope now, you will draw no more afreat while
I sipose RS. lest you & the rest of his freinds by this time, owhere fore
do not write to him butt sub scribe my self
In Antwarp 11 marck
London pickering & robin son
S. my last to you was on the first curitt to which please to be referred then
desired you to provide some cloathes according to patt. e directions included
which I hope you shall performe to both our content I have shipped of
here aboard Adriaen deraes, which went from hence a saturday last
& shall reship att brugges aboard of michiel deraes his brother one bale
N. 11 g 63 p of bed tijkes according to the inclosed invoyce, which
are as good, acurious in goodness & assortement as are to be had for
mony & do send them bree aboard from all charges att arald as
they now yeald here ready mony where fore be confident that no
others can bring them in England for that price, so hope they shall
prove to content: what there shall be over on yd acctt. shall come good
towards the cloathes from tho north on my share, you shall have
the bill of loading from mr. Coots from bruges & where soever I ansern
you freely command him that is
In Antwerp 11 march
London Abram vivians

S. my last to you was on the 4 curitt, to which referre you, sence have

Rekd, both yd of 21 & 25: past I do exspect yd orders for what laces
you might yett want, because itt is now yett good times to buy
that com. thoughett be likedy to vise, I have a fescome in, butt do long
to see pattarnes from you to assort them the better I supose N. 11 & 12 is with
you by this time that you be able to iudge the whole parcell the
more I in quixe the neare I come to the bottom of that trade, & now
I promises my self to be as well accquainted & settled in itt, as any one m
this countrey so you may be confidenf in all shall yd orders bepuictually
observed & in trest menaged as nyowne, besides if you would have atryall
of black Lillersh laces send mee butt a pattarn or vas you would have the
to be made, & I shall gett them made verhape much cheaper then any
were alle a governo — I observe that you had a letter from hull of 22:
pass that John nelson was to depart that days god in heaven send him
well for I want the goods extreainly: thought wee have had & have still
a good northerly winde, yett the betters of yeasterday know not ing of
him: in case N.31: be not in his board & that a vessell lyes ont att sHull
for Rotterdam which departs speedly, lett itt be sent that way
